In the studied North Indian population, the genetic polymorphism in DC-SIGN neck repeats region was rare. Frequency of DC-SIGN homozygous 7/7 genotype (wild type) was 99.72% in healthy controls. Among the entire North Indian individuals genotyped only 1 of 320 (0.31%) from HSN group and 1 of 190 (0.52%) from HSP group were found to have heterozygous 7/8 mutant genotype. The PCR amplified products (921 bp and 852 bp) of heterozygous mutant (7/8) HIV-1 seronegative individual and wild (7/7) samples (852 bp) were cloned successfully into pGEM T-Easy Vector and subjected to restriction enzyme analysis (Fig. 1
). Few positive recombinants clones were selected and subjected to sequencing. An insertion of one full repeat of 69 bp was observed in heterozygous individual (Fig. 2
). Statistical analysis showed that insertion of extra repeat in DC-SIGN exon 4 neck region was not associated with susceptibility to HIV-1 infection in North Indian individuals (Table 3
).
